<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Speed-Time Graph</h3>
</div>
A <strong>speed-time</strong> graph is also known as <strong>velocity-time</strong> graph. <strong>Speed-time</strong> graph shows how speed (velocity) of an object changes over time during a particular journey. This can be used to determine the <strong>acceleration</strong>, <strong>deceleration</strong> and <strong>distance</strong> moved by a body.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Speed</strong> is the distance travelled per time. <strong>Speed</strong> = <sup>distance</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub> 
<br>
<br>
<strong>Acceleration</strong> is the rate at which speed or velocity of a body increases over time. 
<strong>Acceleration</strong> = <sup>speed</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub> <strong>or</strong> <sup>velocity</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Deceleration</strong> is the rate at which the speed/velocity of a body decreases over time. 
<br>
<strong>Deceleration</strong> = <sup>–speed</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub> <strong>or</strong> <sup>–velocity</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Distance</strong> is the space or gap from one point to another point. It is measure in <strong>metres</strong> or <strong>kilometers.</strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example 1</strong>
<br>
<strong>The speed-time graph of a vehicle;</strong>
<br>
<span> <%= image_tag 'speed-timeGraph.png', class: 'carol col-12' %>
<br>
Using the speed-time graph above calculate;
<br>
(i)	The acceleration of the vehicle during first 5seconds.
<br>
(ii)	Distance of the vehicle from the rest before it begins to decelerate.
<br>
(iii)	The deceleration of the vehicle during the final stage.
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
<strong>(i)</strong> <strong>Acceleration between O and A</strong> =  <sup>speed</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub>
<br> 
Change in speed = Final speed − Initial speed 
<br> 
Speed = 10 − 0 =  10m/s and time = 5s − 0s = 5s
<br>
<strong>Acceleration</strong> = <sup>10</sup>&frasl;<sub>5</sub> = <strong>2m/s<sup>2</sup></strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>(ii)</strong> Speed = <sup>distance</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub>          
<br>
<strong>Distance</strong> = average speed x time 
<br>
<strong>Distance travelled in the first stage;</strong>
<br>
Average speed = <sup>(0 + 10)</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub> = <sup>10</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub> = <strong> 5m/s </strong>
<br>
Time = <strong>5s</strong> 
<br>        
Distance = 5 x 5 = <strong>25m</strong>  
<br>     
<strong>Distance travelled in the second stage;</strong>
<br>
From the graph above;
<br>
Time = 20s ─ 5s = <strong>15s</strong>
<br>
Speed = <strong>10m/s</strong>
<br>
<strong>Distance</strong> = 15 x 10 = <strong>150m</strong>
<br>
<strong>The total distance travelled before acceleration</strong> = 25m + 150m = <strong>175m</strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>(iii)</strong> <strong>Deceleration between B and E</strong> = <sup>speed</sup>&frasl;<sub>time</sub>
<br>
Change in speed = Final speed − Initial speed
<br>
Speed = 0 − 10 = <strong>− 10m/s</strong> 
<br> 
Time = 45s – 20s = <strong>25s</strong>
<br>
<strong>Deceleration</strong> = <sup>–10</sup>&frasl;<sub>25</sub> = <strong>− 0.4m/s<sup>2</sup></strong>
<br>
The vehicle decelerates at <strong>0.4m/s<sup>2</sup></strong>	
